    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Few Ways to Spend $60 Billion</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Norman Shiren says major problem with missile defense test is that date was announced; wonders which enemy would inform United States of date and time it intends to launch attack</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Missile Defense With Limits: The ABC's of the Clinton Plan'' (front page, June 30):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Missile Defense With Limits: The ABC's of the Clinton Plan'' (front page, June 30):</p>
        <p>A major problem with the missile defense test announced for July 7 is just that. It is announced! Whether the test succeeds or fails, it is meaningless -- it is doubtful that we can rely on a presumed enemy to inform us as to the date and time that he intends to launch an attack.</p>
        <p>NORMAN SHIREN  Ossining, N.Y., June 30, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a retired physicist.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
